==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ness
<hw>Ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>naes</ets>,
<ets>ns</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>nes</ets>, Sw. <ets>n⟦aum⟧s</ets>,
Dan. <ets>naes</ets>, and E. <ets>nose</ets>. ⟦root⟧ 261. See
<er>Nose</er>.]</ety> <def>A promontory; a cape; a headland.</def>
<rj><au>Hakluyt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Ness</xex> is frequently used as a suffix in the
names of places and promontories; as, Sheer<xex>ness</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-ness</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: -ness
<hw>-ness</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <ety>[AS. <ets>-ness</ets>,
<ets>-nyss</ets>, <ets>-nys</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>-nissi</ets>,
<ets>nussi</ets>, D. <ets>-nis</ets>, OHG. <ets>-nissa</ets>,
<ets>-nass⟦imac⟧</ets>, <ets>-nuss⟦imac⟧</ets>, G. <ets>-nis</ets>,
<ets>-niss</ets>, Goth. <ets>-inasus</ets>.]</ety> <def>A suffix used to
form abstract nouns expressive of <sig>quality</sig> or
<sig>state</sig>; <as>as, good<ex>ness</ex>,
great<ex>ness</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

